[[File:Ohokuninushi family tree.png|thumb|right|250px|Genealogy of Ōkuninushi (according to the Kojiki). Blue indicates male deities, red indicates female deities, and yellow indicates unspecified gender.]] '''Kimata no Kami''' (木俣神, きまたのかみ, also read as Kinomata no Kami or Konomata no Kami) is a deity in Japanese mythology, born to {{ill|Ōnamuchi no Mikoto|ja|大穴牟遅神|1=Ōkuninushi|lt=Ōnamuchi|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Yakami Hime|ja|八上比売|1=Yagami-hime|qq=draft}}.
Yakami Hime was the first wife of Ōnamuchi no Mikoto, but she feared {{ill|Suseri-Hime|ja|須勢理毘売|qq=draft}}, who became Ōnamuchi’s principal wife. Consequently, she left her child in the fork of a tree and returned to her parents' home. The child was thus named "Kimata no Kami," meaning "Deity of the Tree Fork." The deity is also known by the name '''Mii no Kami''' (御井神).
In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft}}, the gender of Kimata no Kami is not specified, but shrine traditions generally identify the deity as the eldest son of Ōnamuchi no Mikoto. Kimata no Kami is widely revered as a deity of trees, water, and safe childbirth.
== Major Shrines == * {{ill|Mii Shrine (Izumo)|ja|御井神社 (出雲市)|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Izumo|ja|島根県出雲市|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Mii Shrine (Yabu)|ja|御井神社 (養父市)|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Yabu|ja|兵庫県養父市|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Mii Shrine (Uda)|ja|御井神社 (宇陀市)|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Uda|ja|奈良県宇陀市|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Tsuda Shrine|ja|津田神社|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Taki|ja|三重県多気町|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Ioi Shrine|ja|五百井神社|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Ritto|ja|滋賀県栗東市|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Keta Wakamiya Shrine|ja|気多若宮神社|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Hida|ja|岐阜県飛騨市|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Mii Shrine (Kakamigahara)|ja|御井神社 (各務原市)|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kakamigahara|ja|岐阜県各務原市|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Mii Shrine (Yōrō)|ja|御井神社 (養老町)|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Yōrō|ja|岐阜県養老郡養老町|qq=draft}}) * {{ill|Ōi Shrine (Kameoka)|ja|大井神社 (亀岡市)|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kameoka|ja|京都府亀岡市|qq=draft}})
